DOMAIN_OVERVIEW:
Property-owning democracy (POD) emerged from John Rawls's late work as an
alternative to welfare-state capitalism, proposing wider dispersal of
productive capital ownership to realize fair equality of opportunity and
prevent domination. The O'Neill & Williamson 2012 edited volume catalyzed
contemporary debate, establishing POD as a distinct regime type beyond
traditional welfare redistribution. Freeman (2013, 2018) clarifies POD's
relationship to the difference principle, while Thomas (2016) synthesizes
POD with republican liberty. Recent work explores POD's application to
housing markets: Erck (2024) develops housing limitarianism within POD
framework; Gregory (2016) critiques homeownership-based POD as anti-
egalitarian; Halliday & Meyer (2024) survey housing justice broadly. Key
tensions include: whether POD requires tenure neutrality or favors
homeownership; how to justify price movements to affected parties; and
whether POD addresses wealth accumulation via housing appreciation.

RELEVANCE_TO_PROJECT:
This domain directly addresses the research question of whether POD applied
to housing meets contractualist justifiability standards. The tension
between POD's commitment to dispersed ownership and the impossibility of
justifying both price appreciation (to newcomers) and price suppression
(to incumbent owners) provides the empirical test case for contractualist
limits on POD regimes.

NOTABLE_GAPS:
Limited work directly addresses contractualist justifiability of housing
price dynamics under POD. Most literature assumes POD is justified without
examining whether specific policies can meet reasonable acceptance tests.
Erck (2024) is the only recent work directly applying POD framework to
housing wealth ceilings, but does not address price dynamics or newcomer
claims.

SYNTHESIS_GUIDANCE:
Distinguish general POD theory (O'Neill & Williamson, Freeman, Thomas) from
housing applications (Erck, Gregory, Halliday & Meyer). Note critiques from
Vallier (2015) challenging POD's economic viability. The tension between
dispersed homeownership as POD's ideal and housing appreciation as source
of inequality is central to the project's contractualist critique.

KEY_POSITIONS:
- POD as distinct regime type: 10 papers - O'Neill, Williamson, Freeman, Thomas, Kerr
- POD applied to housing/wealth: 5 papers - Erck, Gregory, Halliday, James Gregory on homeownership
- Critiques of POD viability: 3 papers - Vallier, Narveson, Raekstad (ambivalent)
====================================================================
